# Alternative Approach

Instead of directly printing characters, we can create a new string and store valid characters inside it.

## Alternative Code

```cpp id="h4k9zp"
#include<iostream>
#include<string>
using namespace std;

class Solution {
public:

    string removeCharacter(string s, char c) {

        string ans = "";

        for(int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {

            if(s[i] != c) {
                ans += s[i];
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

int main() {

    Solution ob;

    string s = "banana";
    char c = 'a';

    cout << ob.removeCharacter(s, c);

    return 0;
}
```

---

# Advantages of Alternative Approach

* Cleaner output
* Easier to reuse
* Returns modified string
* Better for competitive programming
